from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# 2 standard scalar and set y
scaler = StandardScaler()
cases_std = scaler.fit_transform(cases_raw)
cases_std = pd.DataFrame(cases_std, index=cases_raw.index)

# 1 function plots a time-series
def plot_case_by_country(c_ls, std=False):
    # input check
    for i in c_ls:
        assert i in cases_raw.index, 'Does not contain input country: '+i
    assert len(c_ls) >= 2, 'Input List should contain at least 2 Country Names.'
    # set x with dates
    x_date = cases_raw.columns
    # plot wit subplot()
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(c_ls), figsize=(15, 15))
    # set for standardized data
    if std:
        y_case = cases_std.T
    else:
        y_case = cases_raw.T
    for i in range(len(c_ls)):
        axs[i].plot(x_date, y_case[c_ls[i]])
        axs[i].xaxis.set_major_locator(plt.MaxNLocator(10))
        axs[i].set_title(c_ls[i])
    fig.supxlabel('Date')
    if std:
        fig.supylabel('Scaled Case Amount')
        fig.suptitle('Scaled Case Comparison for: '+' '.join(c_ls), fontsize=16)
    else:
        fig.supylabel('Total Case Amount')
        fig.suptitle('Total Case Comparison for: '+' '.join(c_ls), fontsize=16)
    plt.show()

# 1&3 run for 'US', 'China', 'Canada' as default
plot_case_by_country(c_ls=['US', 'China', 'Canada'])
plot_case_by_country(c_ls=['US', 'China', 'Canada'], std=True)

Part 1.4: Answer¶

**1. The trend in US and Canada is quite similar at beginning with a rapid growth in 2020-03 to 2020-05, but only Canada has a huge decline after that. Then both US and Canada have small ups and downs. In comparison, China has a high amount at the very beginning, and it shows a sudden drop while US and Canada has the same the rise(in 2020-03 to 2020-05).

  1. The up and down of the curve means how the number of national total cases change compare to worldwide, if the curve go up then the increasing number of covid cases in this country is faster than the world average, vice versa (because the world average is a flat line at 0). The actual covid cases will not be negative, but within the scaled dataset, the 0 means the average of covid cases globally. Therefore, if a point has a negative value, then in that day, the total national covid case number is below the world average.**

import warnings
warnings.simplefilter("ignore", np.ComplexWarning)

# 1
df_cov_cases = np.dot(cases_std.T, cases_std)/(cases_std.shape[0]-1)

# 2
def get_sorted_eigen(df_cov):
    eigen_values, eigen_vectors = np.linalg.eigh(df_cov)
    args = (-eigen_values).argsort()
    return eigen_values[args], eigen_vectors[:, args]
# 3
eigenValues, eigenVectors = get_sorted_eigen(df_cov_cases)
eigValSum = sum(eigenValues)
expVar = [eigV/eigValSum*100 for eigV in eigenValues]
cumExpVar = np.cumsum(expVar)
plt.bar(range(733), expVar, label='Explained Variance')
plt.plot(cumExpVar, 'r-o', label='Cumulative Explained Variance')
plt.xlim(0,10)
plt.legend()
plt.show()
# 4
print('Part 2.4: Need 3 PCs to reach the 98% variance, which is:', cumExpVar[2])
# 5
def plot_eigen(pc_num=16):
    # set x with dates
    x_date = cases_raw.columns
    # plot wit subplot()
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(pc_num, figsize=(12, 60))

    for i in range(pc_num):
        axs[i].plot(x_date, eigenVectors[:,i])
        axs[i].xaxis.set_major_locator(plt.MaxNLocator(10))
        axs[i].set_title('PC'+str(i+1))
    fig.supxlabel('Date')
    fig.supylabel('Eigenvalue')
    fig.suptitle('Eigenvector with the first '+str(pc_num)+' PC(s)',  fontsize=16)
    fig.tight_layout(rect=[0.01, 0.01, 1, 0.97])
    plt.show()

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

def plot_country_figures(original_df, country_name):
    line_count = 6
    # standard scalar and set y
    scaler_ = StandardScaler()
    df_std = scaler_.fit_transform(original_df)
    df_std = pd.DataFrame(df_std, index=original_df.index)
    # set x with dates, y with cases
    x_date = original_df.columns
    y_case = original_df.loc[country_name]
    # set x-axis showed
    x_date_display = range(0, cases_raw.shape[1], int(np.floor(cases_raw.shape[1]/8)))

    # 3.1 plot the original
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 9))
    plt.plot(x_date, y_case, label='Original', linestyle='dashed', linewidth='4', color='black')
    plt.xticks(x_date_display)
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Case Number')
    plt.ylim(min(y_case)-max(y_case)*0.05, max(y_case)*1.1)
    max_digit = len(str(int(max(y_case))))-1
    plt.ticklabel_format(axis='y', style='sci', scilimits=(max_digit, max_digit))
    plt.title('Original Plot in '+country_name,  fontsize=16)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    # get eigen
    df_cov_ = np.dot(df_std.T, df_std)/(df_std.shape[0]-1)
    eigen_values, eigen_vectors = get_sorted_eigen(df_cov_)
    # set plot PC
    PC_count_ls = [0, 1, 3, 7, 15]

    # 3.2 plot PCs' reconstruction
    df_reconstructed = pd.DataFrame([])
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 9))
    plt.plot(x_date, y_case, label='Original', linestyle='dashed', linewidth='4', color='black')
    for i in range(1, line_count):
        W = eigen_vectors[:, 0:PC_count_ls[i-1]+1]
        projX = np.dot(df_std.loc[country_name,:], W)
        ReconX = np.dot(projX, W.T)
        ReconX_original = scaler_.inverse_transform(ReconX.reshape(1,-1))
        # add reconstructed result to dataframe
        df_re = pd.DataFrame(ReconX_original.T.flatten(), columns=['to PC '+str(PC_count_ls[i-1]+1)])
        df_reconstructed = pd.concat([df_reconstructed, df_re], axis=1)
        # plot
        plt.plot(x_date, ReconX_original.T, label='to PC '+str(PC_count_ls[i-1]+1))
        plt.xticks(x_date_display)
    max_digit = len(str(int(max(y_case))))-1
    plt.ticklabel_format(axis='y', style='sci', scilimits=(max_digit, max_digit))
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Case Number')
    max_digit = len(str(int(max(y_case))))-1
    plt.ticklabel_format(axis='y', style='sci', scilimits=(max_digit, max_digit))
    plt.ylim(min(y_case)-max(y_case)*0.05, max(y_case)*1.1)
    plt.title('Reconstruction with PCs in '+country_name,  fontsize=16)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    df_reconstructed.set_index(original_df.columns, inplace=True)

    # 3.3 plot the reconstructed residual error
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 9))
    i_min = np.argmin([sum(y_case.sub(df_reconstructed.iloc[:,i], axis='index')**2) for i in range(line_count-1)])
    plt.plot(x_date, y_case.sub(df_reconstructed.iloc[:,i_min], axis='index'), label='to PC '+str(PC_count_ls[i_min]+1))
    plt.xticks(x_date_display)
    max_digit = len(str(int(max(y_case.sub(df_reconstructed.iloc[:,i_min], axis='index')))))-1
    plt.ticklabel_format(axis='y', style='sci', scilimits=(max_digit, max_digit))
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Residual Value')
    plt.title('Residual Plot of Reconstruction with PCs in '+country_name,  fontsize=16)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    # 3.4 plot the RMSE with reconstruction
    rmse_ls = []
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 9))
    for i in range(1, 101):
        W = eigen_vectors[:, 0:i]
        projX = np.dot(df_std.loc[country_name,:], W)
        ReconX = np.dot(projX, W.T)
        ReconX_original = scaler_.inverse_transform(ReconX.reshape(1,-1))
        rmse_ls.append(mean_squared_error(y_case, ReconX_original.T, squared=False))
    plt.plot(range(1,101), rmse_ls)
    max_digit = len(str(int(max(rmse_ls))))-1
    plt.ticklabel_format(axis='y', style='sci', scilimits=(max_digit, max_digit))
    plt.xlabel('PC Count')
    plt.ylabel('RMSE')
    plt.title('RMSE Plot of Reconstruction 1-100 PCs in '+country_name,  fontsize=16)
    plt.show()

Part 4: Fashion-MNIST dataset [4 Marks]¶

Fashion-MNIST is a dataset for clothes. Each image in Fashion-MNIST has 28x28 pixels which can be represented in an array with 784 elements. You can take a better look at this dataset in this link

In this part, we are going to use PCA to compress these images. The $x$ matrix below has 1000 images.

Part 4.1: Answer¶

Because we want to get meaningful PCs. If we choose items with a similar shape, a similar sets of pixel columns will be chosen because of having the grayscale variations. This will be very beneficial for the PCA model to combine meaningful pixel patterns and to make dimension reduction(or say picture compression).

Part 4.3: Answer¶

For first few eigenvectors, the first one is capture the main clothing shape, the second is the sleeves, the third is the cuffs and the fourth is the upper shoulders. After those four, the pattern becomes very vague, and for the tenth eigenvector, we can barely tell the clothing shape. Therefore, we can say the trend is focus on main clothing shape first, then shift to small details and other variations of shapes.

# create a function that requires an argument n and plots a random image from the dataset, as well as a reconstruction with the first n-th principal components
import random

def project(W, X, mu):
    return np.dot(X - mu , W)

def reconstruct(W, Y, mu) :
    return np.dot(Y , W.T) + mu

def reconstruct_cloth(n):
    # set random number
    rad = random.choice(idx_cloth)
    # set fig
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
    # plot original
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.imshow(x_cloth.loc[rad].values.reshape(28,28))
    plt.title('Original Plot of #{}'.format(rad))
    # plot reconstruct
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    mean = x_cloth.mean(axis=0)
    P = project(eigenVectors[:, 0:n], x_cloth.loc[rad], mean)
    R = reconstruct(eigenVectors[:, 0:n], P, mean)
    plt.imshow(R.values.reshape(28, 28), cmap = plt.cm.gray)
    plt.title('Reconstruction of #{} with {} PCs'.format(rad, n))
    plt.show()

reconstruct_cloth(50)

Part 4.5: Answer¶

Although we can see some patterns with few PCs(10-50), it is safer to make a guess at about 100 PCs as humans, because many clothes have intricate patterns on them. With smaller PC numbers we cannot identify those well.

Part 4.6: Answer¶

The dataset we generated with only clothing has 281 samples and 784(28*28) pixel columns. Therefore:

  • W: (784,784)
  • Need 100 PCs, so W_op: (784, 100)
  • Projection: X @ W_op = Proj(281, 100)
  • Summarizing: Projection: (281,100) and W_op(784,100), so Total: 106500

Compression Ratio = 784*281/106500 = 2.07x
